This function is messed up enough that it needs its own documentation.

nomask varargs void move_player(string sDirDest, string sDest, string sArrive)

OK, sDirDest can be one of several things:

1) direction#destinationFileName
2) direction only, if sDest has the filename
3) !msgout#destinationFileName
4) !msgout only, if sDest has the filename

But, it gets better.

If 1) or 2), then the message printed to the room being left
is query_msgout... UNLESS 'direction' is 'X', in which case it
uses query_mmsgout. If 3) or 4), the the message is the msgout
portion of sDirDest. In any case, if the direction isn't X and
doesn't begin with !, it is substituted for $D in the entrance
message.

Now, on to sArrive.

1) direction
2) !msgin

If the direction portion of sDirDest is 'X', then query_mmsgin
is used as the entrance message to print to the room the person
is arriving in. Otherwise, if sArrive is a direction, then the
query_msgin message is used with sArrive being substituted into
$D. If sArrive is missing, then the code figures out which exit
in the current room leads back to the previous room, and that is
substituted for $D. If sArrive begins with !, then all of the above
is scrapped and sArrive is used for the incoming message.

Does your head hurt now? Good. Just be glad you didn't have to 
rewrite the damned thing like I did, while still maintaining
backwards compatibility.

